The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Manekshaw better

 New Delhi, Nov. 7 (PTI): The condition of Field Marshal Sam Manekshaw, who was rushed to the armys specialised research and referral hospital here from Tamil Nadu early this morning, has improved, doctors said.

 Manekshaw, 91, was suffering from pneumonia and renal problems, doctors attending to him said.

 He was brought to the referral hospital after being flown in to Delhi from his home in Wellington in Tamil Nadu.

 Manekshaw, the sole surviving field marshal in the Indian Army, led the country to victory in the Bangladesh operation. A veteran of the Burma campaign in World War II, he was decorated with the nations second-highest award, the Padma Vibhushan, after the 1971 Indo-Pak war. 

 He was admitted to the military hospital in Wellington following complaints of breathlessness four days ago.




